Antibody responses were assessed at 2–4 weeks after the MIV boost. All individuals were negative for H5 antibodies by HAI at baseline (table 1
). After MIV boost, the frequency of positive H5 (Indo) HAI responses was greatest when the boost interval was longer (groups 3, 4, and B, table 1). The HAI titre (geometric mean titre [GMT]) was highest in individuals who received DNA priming and were boosted at the longest interval (groups 3, 4, and B; figure 2A and 2D
). H5 binding antibodies assessed by ELISA were present in most individuals after the boost, and the magnitude of the GMT of ELISA responses (table 2
) was highest in DNA primed individuals boosted after the longer 24-week interval (groups 3, 4, and B; figure 2B and E, and table 2). Neutralising antibodies to the H5 were detected in most individuals, and the greatest magnitude of response was also seen in the same groups, (groups 3, 4, and B; figure 2C and F and table 2).
